1. Understanding Malnutrition in India

1.1 Scope and Challenges

India ranks 105 out of the 127 countries on the Global Hunger Index (GHI) and with it’s population of 1.43 billion, comprises 1/3rd of the world’s malnourished children. India also has the highest child wasting rate in the world at 18.7%. Despite efforts, malnutrition costs India as much as 3% of it’s GDP growth each year, making the Prime Minister Narendra Modi’s inconceivably bold claims of making India a $5 trillion economy by 2025. The key issue lies in the government’s one-size-fits-all approach towards malnutrition.

While an avalance of studies attempt to quantify the burned of malnutrition of India and a portion of them also point towards the potential key determinants of malnutrition, sparsely any strive to understand how child malnutrition interacts with its diverse determinants across different regions of the country. Even fewer discuss the inefficiency of focusing at only one aspect to solve malnutrition at a time (for example, Literacy Rate) instead of multidimensional effort. Hence, the data collected serves a two-fold purpose of finding spatial dependencies by employing a of malnutrition Geographically Weighted Regression (GWR) and driving focus away from policies that focus on mending a single determinant.

The National Family Health Survey - 4 (2015-16) is used to collect dristict-level population, nutrition and health data for 7 states of India. These states have the highest malnutrition rates in the country. The spatial data is fetched from Open Street Maps (OSM) using the Nomatim API.

2. National Family Health Survey - 4 For Selected Indian States

Collected by the Ministry of Health and Family Welfare (MOHFW), the NFHS provides the most comprehensive health and nutrition data in India, thereby serving its purpose as the primary data for assessing child malnutrition. The data for this research is district-level and collected for 7 states using the Open Government Data API of the Government of India. The district-level data is publicly available state-wise only. Thereby, it is fetched separately for each of the states and then combined.

Limitations

The data’s limitations arise from the fact that it is a decade old, as it relies on NFHS-4 data (2015–2016), given that NFHS-5 data is not yet publicly available at the district level. The limitation is huge, since the overall trends have not changed from NFHS 4 to 5. The OGD limitation itself havs a limitation, for it does not allow the choice of parameters.

2.1: Fetching NFHS Data

#This code chunk uses the Open Government Data API provided by the Indian Government to fetch district-level data from 7 Indian states.

base_url <- list( #Creating a list of base_urls for each state. This is a downside of the OGD API, for it does not allow setting of parameters. Thereby, base urls need to be set separately for each state.
  uta = "https://api.data.gov.in/resource/5144892d-5154-4403-8307-1136f08e8da1",
  bih = "https://api.data.gov.in/resource/1311af83-90a7-4bf9-a269-509328ea8383",
  guj = "https://api.data.gov.in/resource/e9c93e1e-52d0-4791-9151-8e3a89b11e27",
  jha = "https://api.data.gov.in/resource/dd94ec3d-ab59-40e1-9b73-cfc0bce084d6",
  chh = "https://api.data.gov.in/resource/1d7ac50c-ad51-4645-bd7b-31c9200811c4",
  kar = "https://api.data.gov.in/resource/5d940e15-09cb-4139-8758-5b59513f053c",

)

#Setting function to fetch data only if it doesn't already exist
fetch_and_save <- function(base, state_name) {
    data <- GET(base, 
                query = list(`api-key` = key_get("ogd_key"), format = "csv", limit = 100)) #Actually fetching data from the API
    Sys.sleep(5) # Respecting API limits by adding sleeo
    raw_data <- content(data, as = "text", encoding = "UTF-8") %>% read_csv() #Extracting the API data as text and then converting it to a tibble
    return(raw_data)
  }

#Applying the fetch and save function to each state of interest.
uta <- fetch_and_save(base_url$uta, "Uttar Pradesh")
bih <- fetch_and_save(base_url$bih, "Bihar")
guj <- fetch_and_save(base_url$guj, "Gujarat")
jha <- fetch_and_save(base_url$jha, "Jharkhand")
chh <- fetch_and_save(base_url$chh, "Chhattisgarh")
kar <- fetch_and_save(base_url$kar, "Karnataka")
meg <- fetch_and_save(base_url$meg, "Meghalaya")

2.2: Making NFHS Data Tidy

#This code chunk cleans the state-wise tibbles created from API data to make them tidy.

#Setting function to tidy the data and save it only if it does not exist.
tidy_and_save <- function(tibble, state_name) {
    tidy_data <- tibble %>% 
      filter(!row_number() %in% c(86, 87, 91, 92, 93)) %>% #Filtering out duplicate rows. These rows are duplicated in tables across all states of India.
      select(-starts_with("Note of")) %>% #Removing columns not required.
      pivot_longer(
        cols = -matches("^Residence"), #Pivoting all columns except the one which starts with Residence
        names_to = "District_Area", #Saving the District-Area values
        values_to = "Value" #Saving the numeric values
      ) %>%
      separate( #Separating District name and area (Urban, Rural, Total) into two columns.
        col = "District_Area",
        into = c("District", "Area"),
        sep = " - ",
        extra = "merge",
        fill = "right"
      ) %>%
      rename_with(~ gsub("^Residence.*", "Particular", .x), matches("^Residence")) %>% #Renaming the column starting with Residence.
      mutate(State = state_name) %>% 
      pivot_wider( #Pivoting the tibble again such that each NFHS metric has its own column
        names_from = "Particular",
        values_from = "Value"
      ) %>%
      rename_with(~ gsub("^\\d+\\.\\s*", "", .x)) #Removing the numeric prefix from the beginning of the column names.
    return(tidy_data)
  }

#Applying the tidy and save function to each state of interest.
uta_tidy <- tidy_and_save(uta, "Uttar Pradesh")
bih_tidy <- tidy_and_save(bih, "Bihar")
guj_tidy <- tidy_and_save(guj, "Gujarat")
jha_tidy <- tidy_and_save(jha, "Jharkhand")
chh_tidy <- tidy_and_save(chh, "Chhattisgarh")
kar_tidy <- tidy_and_save(kar, "Karnataka")
meg_tidy <- tidy_and_save(meg, "Meghalaya")

3. Open Street Map Data

The secondary data, sourced from the Nominatim API of OpenStreetMap, provides geocoded location information to enhance the spatial analysis of district-level malnutrition trends from the NFHS dataset. This data adds geographic coordinates and administrative boundaries, enabling detailed visualizations and spatial regressions. The raw data is sourced as text and finally coded as a sf dataframe.

Limitations

Challenges of the data include ambiguous place names (e.g., “Agra” as a city and district) and inconsistent representation of administrative units, leading to duplicates and gaps. Rigorous data cleaning, filtering, and ethical practices (e.g., adhering to API rate limits) address these issues.

3.1: Fetching Spatial Data

#This code chunk uses the Nomatim API of OSM to fetch boundary data for all districts of each of the seven states present in the NFHS dataset,

secondary_site <- "https://nominatim.openstreetmap.org/search" #Setting the base api url

unique_districts <- primary_data %>% distinct(state, district) #Filtering out unique state-district combinations

spatial_list <- list() #Initialising an empty list to save the raw spatial data fetched using the Nomatim API.

for (i in seq(1, nrow(unique_districts))) { #Initialising for loop to iterate over the unique State-District combinations from primary data to fetch boundary data for them.
  state <- unique_districts$state[i] #Extracting state value from the dataframe "unique_districts"
  district <- unique_districts$district[i] #Extracting district value from the dataframe "unique_districts"
  
  #Setting parameters for the Nomatim API within the for loop.
  params <- list(
    country = "India",
    state = state,
    county = district,
    featureType = "settlement",
    format = "geojson",
    addressdetails = 1,
    polygon_geojson = 1
  )
  
  Sys.sleep(1) #Adding sleep to pause for 2 seconds between two consecutive api calls to respect API call rate.
  response <- GET(secondary_site, query = params) #Actually fetching data from the API
  
  geo_data <- st_read(content(response, as = "text", encoding = "UTF-8"), quiet = TRUE) #Converting API data received into text format
  geo_data <- geo_data %>% mutate(State = state) #The normatim API does not include state name in its outcome. Hence, adding state name for clarity
  spatial_list[[i]] <- geo_data #Adding district-wise text data to the initialised list
}

3.2: Making Spatial Data Tidy and Creating Secondary Data

#This code converts first converts the raw spatial data into a tibble and then into a shapefile. Finally, it deals with some issues of the Indian nomenclature.

  spatial_tibble <- do.call(rbind, spatial_list) #Converting text data within "spatial_list" to a tibble
  #Cleaning the spatial tibble to extract ONLY boundary data. This is done to navigate through issues with Indian nomenclature where certain counties, districts and even infrastructural amenities have the same name.
  secondary_data <- spatial_tibble %>% 
  filter(category == "boundary") %>%
  distinct(name, .keep_all = TRUE) %>% #removing duplicates
  select(name, geometry, State) %>%
  rename(district = name)
  
  secondary_data <- secondary_data %>% clean_names() #Cleaning column names.
#This code chunk fetches the international boundary of India useing the rnaturalearth package.

india_boundary <- ne_countries(scale = "medium", country = "India", returnclass = "sf") #Extracting the international boundary of India.

4. Data Transformations

4.1 Transformation 1

This transformation uses the K-Nearest Neighbours to fill all the missing values. The NNs are complete cases chosen on a distance metric. In this cases, the average of 7 complete cases are chosen to fill each value.

#This code chunk fills all the missing values using the K nearest neighbour algorithm and creates a new dataframe to save all transformations.

primary_data <- primary_data %>%
  mutate(across(where(is.character), as.factor)) #Typecasting all character variables as factors

transformed_primary_data <- knnImputation(primary_data, k = 7) #Filling NA values using the KNN algorithm where number of neart neighbours = 7

4.2 Transformation 2

This transformation simply creates the inverse percentages of 6 variables from the dataset. These variables are further used to compute a district-wise malnorishment index.

#This code chunk creates inverse percentages for some NFHS metrics to be used in the malnourishment index.

transformed_primary_data$`children_age_9_59_months_who_did_not_receive_a_vitamin_a_dose_in_last_6_months_percent` <- 100 - transformed_primary_data$`children_age_9_59_months_who_received_a_vitamin_a_dose_in_last_6_months_percent` #Creating a variable to observe % of children who do not receive a Vitman A dose.

transformed_primary_data$`children_under_age_3_years_not_breastfed_within_one_hour_of_birth_percent` <- 100 - transformed_primary_data$`children_under_age_3_years_breastfed_within_one_hour_of_birth8_percent` #Creating a variable to observe % of children who are not breastfed within an hour of birth

transformed_primary_data$`children_under_age_6_months_not_exclusively_breastfed_percent` <- 100 - transformed_primary_data$`children_under_age_6_months_exclusively_breastfed9_percent` #Creating a variable to observe % of children who dare not exclusively breastfed for 6 months.

transformed_primary_data$`children_age_12_23_months_fully_not_immunized_bcg_measles_and_3_doses_each_of_polio_dpt_percent` <- 100 - transformed_primary_data$`children_age_12_23_months_fully_immunized_bcg_measles_and_3_doses_each_of_polio_dpt_percent` #Creating a variable to observe % of children who are not immunised.

transformed_primary_data$`children_age_6_8_months_not_receiving_solid_or_semi_solid_food_and_breastmilk_percent` <- 100 - transformed_primary_data$`children_age_6_8_months_receiving_solid_or_semi_solid_food_and_breastmilk9_percent` #Creating a variable to observe % of children are not fed solid or semi-solid food or breastmilk.

transformed_primary_data$`total_children_age_6_23_months_not_receiving_an_adequate_diet9_10_percent` <- 100 - transformed_primary_data$`total_children_age_6_23_months_receiving_an_adequate_diet9_10_percent` #Creating a variable to observe % of children who have an inadequate diet.

4.3 Transformation 3

This transformation creates a malnourishment index as a weighted average of 13 health and nutrition metrics. The index considers the mother’s health apart from the child’s health.

#This code chunk creates a malnourishment index as a weighted average of 13 NFHS metrics. 

transformed_primary_data$malnourishment_index <- (0.1*transformed_primary_data$prevalence_of_diarrhoea_reported_in_the_last_2_weeks_preceding_the_survey_percent) + (0.08*transformed_primary_data$children_age_9_59_months_who_did_not_receive_a_vitamin_a_dose_in_last_6_months_percent) + (0.08*transformed_primary_data$children_under_age_3_years_not_breastfed_within_one_hour_of_birth_percent) + (0.1*transformed_primary_data$children_under_age_6_months_not_exclusively_breastfed_percent) + (0.15*transformed_primary_data$children_under_5_years_who_are_severely_wasted12_percent) + (0.15*transformed_primary_data$children_under_5_years_who_are_stunted11_percent) + (0.08*transformed_primary_data$pregnant_women_age_15_49_years_who_are_anaemic_11_0_g_dl_percent) + (0.08*transformed_primary_data$children_under_5_years_who_are_underweight11_percent) + (0.07*transformed_primary_data$children_age_12_23_months_fully_not_immunized_bcg_measles_and_3_doses_each_of_polio_dpt_percent) + (0.05*transformed_primary_data$women_age_15_19_years_who_were_already_mothers_or_pregnant_at_the_time_of_the_survey_percent) + (0.06*transformed_primary_data$children_age_6_8_months_not_receiving_solid_or_semi_solid_food_and_breastmilk_percent) + (0.06*transformed_primary_data$total_children_age_6_23_months_not_receiving_an_adequate_diet9_10_percent) + (0.05*transformed_primary_data$total_unmet_need_percent)

4.4 Transformation 4

This transformation computes a district-wise ratio of female to male literacy rates. Then, another variable which categorises the literacy ratio in 3 bins is created.

#This code chunk creates 2 new variables. The first is the ratio of female to male literacy rates. The second bins this ratio as low, medium or high. The ratio is crucial for further analysis.

transformed_primary_data$literacy_ratio <- transformed_primary_data$women_who_are_literate_percent / transformed_primary_data$men_who_are_literate_percent #Computing the literacy ratio (Female : Male)

transformed_primary_data <- transformed_primary_data %>% mutate(literacy_ratio_category = case_when(
      literacy_ratio < 0.7 ~ "Low",
      literacy_ratio >= 0.7 & women_who_are_literate_percent / men_who_are_literate_percent <= 0.9 ~ "Medium",
      literacy_ratio > 0.9 ~ "High")) #Creating a categorical variable and binning the literacy ratio.

4.5 Transformation 5

This transformation extracts the area of each of the districts using its sf polygons and bins them as small or large. Then, the longitude and latitude of the centroid of each district are extracted, which are important for creation of visualisations.

#This code chunk derives the area of each district in the secondary OSM dataset and also extracts the longitude and latitude of the centroid of each district.

transformed_secondary_data <- secondary_data %>% mutate(area = st_area(geometry)) #Creating a new area variable and saving district area into it.

transformed_secondary_data$area <- (transformed_secondary_data$area) %>% set_units(km^2) #Converting area values from m^2 to km^2.

transformed_secondary_data <- transformed_secondary_data %>% mutate(district_size = ifelse(area <= median(area, na.rm = TRUE), "Small", "Large")) #Categorising a district as small or large on the basis of area and converting normal tibble into a simplefeatures dataframe.

transformed_secondary_data <- transformed_secondary_data %>% mutate(centre = st_centroid(geometry)) #Extracting point coordinates for the centre of each district

transformed_secondary_data$longitude <- st_coordinates(transformed_secondary_data$centre)[, 1] #Saving longitude value of centroid of each district
transformed_secondary_data$latitude <- st_coordinates(transformed_secondary_data$centre)[, 2] #Saving latitude value of centroid of each district

4.6.1 Combining Datasets

#This code chunk combines primary and secondary data for future analysis and saves it as a csv if it does not exist in the system.

combined_data <- merge(transformed_primary_data, transformed_secondary_data, by = "district") %>% arrange(district) %>% arrange(state.x) %>% st_as_sf() %>% clean_names() #Combining the two tibbles and cleaning column names.

5. Visualisations and Correlation

5.1: Literacy and Malnutrition

India claims to allocate about 0.5% of its annual GDP to adult education in order to reduce malnutrition. While the importance of literacy cannot be discarded, it is not what helps malnutrition on the broader level. While female education still considerably adds to the child’s health, male literacy barely moves the needle. The ratio of female to male literacy in each district weekly finds a spot between the two.

The impact of literacy does not change much between small and large districts either.

6.2.2 Saving Non- Tabular Data IN SQL Database

Saving non-tabular data in SQL can only be done in the form of binary values.

#This code chunk saves raw RDS data and Image output in SQL as BLOBs.
#The echo is set to FALSE here since the code chunk outputs 0 and 1 message from the database.

dbExecute(cmi, "
  CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS non_tabular_data (
      id INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT,
      file_name TEXT,
      file_type TEXT NOT NULL,
      file_data BLOB
  )
") #Creating table to save BLOB data

read_file_as_raw <- function(file_path) { #Setting function to read in image and rds data and then convert them to BLOB (binary data).
  raw_data <- readBin(file_path, what = "raw", n = file.info(file_path)$size) #reading in raw data
  return(raw_data)}

save_file_to_db <- function(file_path, file_type) { #Setting function to save data to database.
  file_data <- read_file_as_raw(file_path) #Using read_file_as_raw function within the current function to read in the data
  file_name <- basename(file_path) #Extracting file name

  dbExecute(cmi, "
    INSERT INTO non_tabular_data (file_name, file_type, file_data) VALUES (?, ?, ?)",
    params = list(file_name, file_type, list(file_data))) #Inserting file into databse
}

save_rds_to_db <- function(rds_path) { #Setting function to save rds file
  save_file_to_db(rds_path, 'rds') #Using save_file_to_db within current function
}

save_png_to_db <- function(png_path) { #Setting function to save png file
  save_file_to_db(png_path, 'png') #Using save_file_to_db within current function
}

save_rds_to_db(spatial_data_path) #Actually saving rds file

plot_list <- list("scatter_ratio", "scatter_female", "scatter_male", "malnourishment_map_bihar", "malnourishment_map_meghalaya") #Creating a list of plots created.

for (i in plot_list){ #Initialising loop to save each of the png plots
  plot_path <- file.path(output_dir, paste0(i, ".png"))
  save_png_to_db(plot_path)}  #Actually saving png file
